    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/pump-hemolysis-bench-comparison",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Bench-scale hemolysis validation against FDA pump experimental dataset",
      "description": "CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values compared against published FDA pump experimental measurements across all five flow-speed operating points. Agreement within 18% for four of five conditions; the fifth condition (low-flow, high-speed) shows a 31% over-prediction of NIH, attributed to transitional flow regime effects not fully captured by the steady-state k-omega SST turbulence closure. This edge case is noted as a known limitation of the turbulence model selection. The overall assessment concludes that model performance is adequate and risk is acceptable."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/mesh-independence-study",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Mesh independence study — three refinement levels",
      "description": "Grid convergence index (GCI) computed across coarse, medium, and fine meshes (4.2M, 11.7M, and 28.4M elements). GCI for NIH at the worst-case operating point is 3.1%, satisfying the 5% threshold. Discretization error is bounded and acceptable for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/solver-verification",
